g.text: POPS:
SOURCES AND MAGNIFICATION
POPs can travel for incredibly long distances in the air
away from their original sources. Soil is a major repository
for POPs, which largely include pesticides used in
agriculture. Despite many countrie banning or restricting
use of pesticides, they are hard to break down and
continue to persist in soil due to their long half-lives.
POPs can be absorbed by plants,
wildlife and people. POPs are stored
mostly in fat. Animals (predators) that
eat other animals (prey) are higher on
the food chain and can build up POPs
more easily. This is called
biomagnification.
Water is a major channel through which POPs – insoluble in water
– are deposited and transported along currents. Once having
contaminated the water on which organisms depend, POPs often
find their way into the plants, fish, and meat that humans eat.
Industrial POPs include polychlorinated
biphenyls, which have a variety of applications
including as coolants and lubricants. Industrial
POPs also include unintentional byproducts
of industrial processes such as dioxins and
furans.

text.tspan: POPS CAN TRAVEL THROUGH AIR OR WATER CURRENTS FOR THOUSANDS OF KILOMETERS.
ON WARM DAYS, THEY CAN EVAPORATE IN THE AIR. THEY CAN ALSO TRAVEL LONG DISTANCES
THROUGH A ‘GRASSHOPPER EFFECT’ UNTIL THEY REACH COLD ARCTIC REGIONS.
